Command workbench.action.files.saveAll is not executed by statusbaritem. Issue is like #12214.

- VSCode Version: Code 1.7.1 (02611b40b24c9df2726ad8b33f5ef5f67ac30b44, 2016-11-03T13:53:14.822Z)
- OS Version: Windows_NT ia32 10.0.14393

Steps to Reproduce:

[saveall.zip](https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/files/573780/saveall.zip)
1. Unzip extension saveAll
2. npm install
3. execute extension in VSCode
4. click on created StatusBarItem "Save All"

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/13434739/20037274/e129f5a6-a41c-11e6-9dd7-5550f7a643c9.png)


Code needed to reproduce issue:
`
export function activate(context: vscode.ExtensionContext) {
    const statusBarItem = vscode.window.createStatusBarItem(vscode.StatusBarAlignment.Left, 1);
    statusBarItem.command = 'workbench.action.files.saveAll';
    statusBarItem.text = 'Save All';
    statusBarItem.show();
    context.subscriptions.push(statusBarItem);
}
`

## My mistake, I searched a couple more times and found this already documented at #15013.

- VSCode Version: 1.7.1
- OS Version: Windows 10 64 bit (1607)

Steps to Reproduce:

1. Open a `.scss` file
2. Insert a line comment

![](http://g.recordit.co/Svh4DwGf02.gif)

In prior VS Code versions, inserting a line comment would add a comment via `//`, like so
```
.foo {
   color: $uncommented;
   // background-color: $commented;
}
```

Now the default behavior is to insert a `/* */`, which has a fundamentally different meaning in SCSS (these comments are included in the build by default).

Using Polymer sometimes requires the use of mixins to style certain elements but VSCode is marking it as an error although it is valid CSS.

- VSCode Version: 1.7.1
- OS Version: Windows 10.0.14393

Steps to Reproduce:
1. Create a css file add the following:
`.mixin-test {
        --mixin: {
          /* Rules */
        };
      };`
